K-Means Clustering of Stocks

A stock is a type of investment that represents an ownership share in a company. Investors buy stocks that they think will go up in value over time. Therefore, AI could offer investors a great tool that would help them make more money by assisting them in choosing the stock with a better chance of increasing in share value.

We used clustering to make sense of the numerous stock data that the stock market offer. We also used it to group data into similar clusters. Then, these clustered data would help us in stock prediction. We used the K-Means clustering algorithm since our data is unlabeled and for reliability. The goal of this algorithm is to find groups in the data, with the number of groups represented by the variable K.

An indicator is a mathematical calculation based on historic price, volume, or open interest information. Investors use these indicators to forecast financial market direction. Therefore, it only makes sense that we choose to cluster our stock data according to the indicators that offer useful structure to the data.

After some research we found out that the best indicators to cluster our data with are these three.

Return on Assets: It indicates how efficient the company is managing its assets to generate earning. Thus, if its making a good job, we should be able to see a good return on assets.

Return on Equity: It indicates how the company is using its equity to make profit which is another company performance indicator.

Return on Investment: It indicates how well this stock has been doing as an investment.

Therefore, if a stock is doing great in all of these indicators, we should expect an increase in the stock value. This is still not enough for accurate prediction, but it does yield higher probability.

We define the list of attributes we want to extract and work with.

For more accurate clustering and since K-means is sensitive to outliers, we have to remove all the outlier companies that have extreme indicator values. For example, a company might have 16000% as a Return on Equity value but this is not very reflective of a traditional company. This might happen due to having a small equity base with large revenue in the denominator. Since K-means is sensitive to outliers we removed them.

After some research, we found out that a company is considered to be an outlier if it has more than 40% for Return on Equity and 30% for either Return on Assets or Return on Investment.

In our code, we kept all rows that have their equity under 40, and their assets and investments under 30.

First we define our attribute locations (we already know which column is on which index) with the new constraint, then we filter the dataframe accordingly.

In [10]:

assets = attributes_df.iloc[:,1] <30
investments = attributes_df.iloc[:,2] <30

attributes_df = attributes_df[equity & assets & investments]

As we said K-means is really sensitive to outliers, hence why we have to normalize the data using scalers that are present in sklearn. There are multiple scalers present but most of them are susceptible to outliers, hence we are going to use the robust scaler which is explained below.

Here we scale the data so that it fits in a range between 0 and 1. Mathematically we take each data point, subtract the minimum from it, and then divide it by the difference of the maximum value and the minimum value. Again, this is sensitive to outliers as the maximum amount would be the outlier.

min-max scaler: This method scales data to be between 0 and 1 by subtracting the minimum from each data point and dividing it by the difference of the max and min values. This is extremely sensitive to outliers as the min and max values tend to obviously be outliers.

standard scaler: This method divides the mean by the standard deviation after subtracting it from each data point. This scaler is sensitive to outliers.

robust scaler: This method uses the the difference between smallest value and the largest value of the middle 50% of a set of data instead of the minimum and maximum. Hence, this method is the least susceptible to outliers which we will use.

Sklearn already has the methods made for us so we only have to bring them to our code.

Since we have large data sets with multiple attributes, we decided to include Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to make our model have less redundant data and run faster. In our project, the use of PCA is simply to check whether having 3 attributes is actually beneficial to us or whether it barely adds new information. In this way, we can keep only the most essential attributes and get rid of the useless ones.

Luckily, sklearn has PCA made for us, so we combine pca and numpy's cumulative sum method in order to plot the variance.

In [13]:
pca = PCA().fit(scaled_robust)

plt.figure()
plt.plot(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))

plt.xlabel('Number of Attributes', fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel('Variance %', fontsize = 15) 
plt.title('Explained Variance', fontsize = 20)

plt.show()

As we can see from the graph, with 2 attributes we achieve a variance of 100%. This means that if we are to choose 2 attributes only we will explain the same amount of variance as 3 with less redundency and calculation. K-means clustering is a simple algorithm to understand and thats why people use it. However, K-means clustering is not a fast algorithm and it is susceptible to redundency. While our sample data is low and execution time will still be in seconds, we included this step in order to explain more about the nature of K-means.

Now that we are done with visualizing the model in order to understand it, we will start clustering down below.

In order to K-means cluster, we have to determine K. Now there are many approaches to determine K, but we opted with the silhouette approach as it is simple to visualize. Silhouette analysis approach studies the distance between each cluster. And since we want our clusters to be distinct from each other, we need our clusters to be distanced from each other. Silhouette approach measures that distance as a silhouette coefficient in a range between (-1,1) where 1 indicates that the clusters are far from each other which is the desired result. We will test multiple Ks to find out which K results in the highest coefficient in order to choose.

We will start with 2 clusters till 10 as having 1 cluster is illogical.

We will be using sklearn heavily here, especially kmeans and metrics which are imported above. We will base our metric on the euclidean metric which is the most popular to base our silhouette score on.

We will do one calculation with no PCA and another with PCA.

In [16]:
results_dict= {}

for k in range(2, 11):
    
    print("-"*120)

    results_dict[k] = {}

    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=0).fit(scaled_robust)

    sil_score = metrics.silhouette_score(scaled_robust, kmeans.labels_, metric='euclidean')
    
    results_dict[k]['silhouette_score'] = sil_score
    results_dict[k]['model'] = kmeans
    print("Number of Clusters: {}".format(k))
    print('Silhouette Score:', sil_score)

print("-"*120)

Now looking at the data, generally our clusters silhouette should exceed the silhouette score line which is in red. This happens with both clusters 2 and 3 models which we are happy with.

Another way of determining the better K is to look at the width of the silhouettes. You need the width to be similar for all silhouettes, and looking at 2 clusters we find that cluster 0 is way wider than cluster 1, while looking at 3 clusters we find out that the width is more acceptable than 2 but still its not that acceptable. While on 5, we have some noticable differences between several clusters but it is more acceptable than 3 as we have clusters that are almost identical. Based on this analysis, we chose to go with K = 5 as the optimal K.

The negative values are the outliers, it is reasonable and acceptable to have outliers as you can't escape not having them in a world that is not perfect.

Now we will create scatterplots to visualize clustering.

We mentioned our optimal K that we chose is 5, but for demonstration we will be visualizing a scatter plot for clusters 2, 3, and 5.

We will be using KMeans from sklearn to apply clustering, and will be using matlib in order to scatter.

In [20]:
clusters = [2,3,5]

for cluster in clusters:
    
    print('-'*120)
    
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters= cluster, random_state=0).fit(scaled_robust)

    centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_
    C1 = centers[:, 0]
    C2 = centers[:, 1]
    C3 = centers[:, 2]

    figure = plt.figure()
    a = Axes3D(figure)

    x = scaled_robust[:,0]
    y = scaled_robust[:,1]
    z = scaled_robust[:,2]
    
    names = attributes_df.columns
    a.set_xlabel(names[0])
    a.set_ylabel(names[1])
    a.set_zlabel(names[2])

    a.scatter(x, y, z, c = kmeans.labels_.astype(float), cmap='rainbow')
    a.scatter(C1, C2, C3, marker="x", color='red')

    plt.title('Visualization of K-means clustering with {} clusters'.format(cluster), fontweight='bold')

    plt.show()

As we can see, the clustering structure in both runs is similar. We get a 2D model instead of a 3D model in PCA as PCA is a dimensional reduction method. We can pinpoint which clusters have the wide silhouette based on their density. For example, in the 5 clusters model, the clusters on the left have incredibly high density with respect to the clusters on the left.

Where are the outliers present?

Outliers are usually present on the edges of the clustering, they are mostly promiment in the 3 clusters model between the left and the middle cluster.

Why is there a difference in density?

Usually most companies are present at the end of the model since they are subpar/average when they deliver on our metrics we chose (attributes), there are less companies doing above average, and even less companies doing extremely well on 1 metric or all metrics.

Now to apply our information. We test a sample of data we got from our attributes dataframe using 5 clusters in order to predict in which cluster the data will be present.

This will help us when predicting stocks to find out what stocks are related to each other in their behavior. Knowing this information, it helps us predict whichever stock is going to rise as a result of its sister stock in the cluster is rising.

Conclusion

K-means clustering is an easy to understand unsupervised machine-learning clustering technique that is one of the most popular techniques used. Clustering is often accompanied with classification as the clusters already divide data into sets that need to be classified. While we did not apply classification in our model, we learned that there are similarities between some stocks based on the three attributes that we chose which are return on equity, return on assets, and return on investment.

The problems we faced in our model is the amount of density at the lower end of our metrics. This allows us to question choices in our approach to clulstering like if the metrics we chose were the best or if the K we chose is the most optimal one.

Moreover, this whole approach raises a lot of questions. How would our data perform with a different type of clustering algorithm? How would filtering the results impact our model? Does increasing or decreasing the threshold of our chosen attributes lead to a better silhouette score and hence better clustering?

This shows the importance of trial and error in K-means clustering. Approaching data is never perfect, and in order to find out the percentage of our success we must keep trying with different sets of datas, altering our metrics, or choosing different K and analyzing the results while comparing them with each other in order to find out what is the most optimal way to implement K-means clustering on stocks.
